WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.244 --> 00:00:14.106
In Oxford in the 1950s,
在20世纪50年代的牛津

2
00:00:14.106 --> 00:00:17.874
there was a fantastic doctor, who was very unusual,
有一位很优秀,不寻常的医生

3
00:00:17.874 --> 00:00:19.906
named Alice Stewart.
她叫Alice Stewart

4
00:00:19.906 --> 00:00:23.049
And Alice was unusual partly because, of course,
Alice很不寻常,因为她是个女的医生

5
00:00:23.049 --> 00:00:26.529
she was a woman, which was pretty rare in the 1950s.
这对于在20世纪50年代很罕见了

6
00:00:26.529 --> 00:00:28.640
And she was brilliant, she was one of the,
她非常厉害,是当时最年轻的

7
00:00:28.640 --> 00:00:33.456
at the time, the youngest Fellow to be elected to the Royal College of Physicians.
"皇家医师学院"最年轻的学员之一

8
00:00:33.456 --> 00:00:37.213
She was unusual too because she continued to work after she got married,
她很不寻常还因为在她结婚生子后

9
00:00:37.213 --> 00:00:39.308
after she had kids,
她还继续工作

10
00:00:39.308 --> 00:00:42.316
and even after she got divorced and was a single parent,
甚至在她离婚成为单亲妈妈之后

11
00:00:42.316 --> 00:00:44.599
she continued her medical work.
她继续着她的医学工作

12
00:00:44.599 --> 00:00:48.719
And she was unusual because she was really interested in a new science,
她很不寻常还因为她对一门新的科学感兴趣

13
00:00:48.719 --> 00:00:51.343
the emerging field of epidemiology,
当时新出现的流行病学

14
00:00:51.343 --> 00:00:54.831
the study of patterns in disease.
对于疾病规律的研究

15
00:00:54.831 --> 00:00:56.999
But like every scientist, she appreciated
但跟每个科学家一样,她知道为了让她

16
00:00:56.999 --> 00:00:59.255
that to make her mark, what she needed to do
出众,她需要寻找到难题

17
00:00:59.255 --> 00:01:03.773
was find a hard problem and solve it.
然后解决她

18
00:01:03.773 --> 00:01:06.317
The hard problem that Alice chose
Alice当时选择的难题是

19
00:01:06.317 --> 00:01:09.715
was the rising incidence of childhood cancers.
童年期癌症发生率的上升

20
00:01:09.715 --> 00:01:11.905
Most disease is correlated with poverty,
大多数疾病都是跟贫穷有关的

21
00:01:11.905 --> 00:01:14.174
but in the case of childhood cancers,
不过在童年期癌症的问题上,

22
00:01:14.174 --> 00:01:16.778
the children who were dying seemed mostly to come
这些垂死的孩子似乎大多数

23
00:01:16.778 --> 00:01:19.223
from affluent families.
都从富裕家庭中而来

24
00:01:19.223 --> 00:01:20.966
So, what, she wanted to know,
因为她想知道,怎样才能

25
00:01:20.966 --> 00:01:24.048
could explain this anomaly?
解释这样一种特殊现象呢?

26
00:01:24.048 --> 00:01:26.831
Now, Alice had trouble getting funding for her research.
当时,Alice很难为她的研究筹备到资金

27
00:01:26.831 --> 00:01:28.822
In the end, she got just 1,000 pounds
最后,她只得到了1000英镑,

28
00:01:28.822 --> 00:01:31.077
from the Lady Tata Memorial prize.
从Lady Tata纪念奖得来的

29
00:01:31.077 --> 00:01:33.620
And that meant she knew she only had one shot
这意味着她知道她对于收集数据

30
00:01:33.620 --> 00:01:35.662
at collecting her data.
只有一次机会

31
00:01:35.662 --> 00:01:38.139
Now, she had no idea what to look for.
她完全不知道应当寻找什么

32
00:01:38.139 --> 00:01:41.255
This really was a needle in a haystack sort of search,
这对于需要大量数据的研究来说是一个沉重打击

33
00:01:41.255 --> 00:01:43.877
so she asked everything she could think of.
因此她问了所有她能想到的东西

34
00:01:43.877 --> 00:01:45.710
Had the children eaten boiled sweets?
这些孩子有没有吃煮沸的甜食?

35
00:01:45.710 --> 00:01:47.783
Had they consumed colored drinks?
他们有没有喝花里胡哨的饮料?

36
00:01:47.783 --> 00:01:49.430
Did they eat fish and chips?
他们是不是吃油炸鱼和薯片了?

37
00:01:49.430 --> 00:01:51.438
Did they have indoor or outdoor plumbing?
他们是不是使用过户内或者户外的铅制品?

38
00:01:51.438 --> 00:01:54.854
What time of life had they started school?
他们什么时候开始上学的?

39
00:01:54.854 --> 00:01:58.222
And when her carbon copied questionnaire started to come back,
而当她的用碳做的调查问卷回来的时候,

40
00:01:58.222 --> 00:02:01.142
one thing and one thing only jumped out
只有一个明显的数据

41
00:02:01.142 --> 00:02:03.678
with the statistical clarity of a kind that
显示了出来,

42
00:02:03.678 --> 00:02:06.518
most scientists can only dream of.
这是大多数科学家都无法想象的

43
00:02:06.518 --> 00:02:08.438
By a rate of two to one,
三分之二的这些由于癌症而死的孩子

44
00:02:08.438 --> 00:02:10.519
the children who had died
他们的母亲在怀孕的时候

45
00:02:10.519 --> 00:02:16.814
had had mothers who had been X-rayed when pregnant.
都做过X光检查

46
00:02:16.814 --> 00:02:21.319
Now that finding flew in the face of conventional wisdom.
这个发现对于传统观念是一大冲击

47
00:02:21.319 --> 00:02:23.226
Conventional wisdom held
传统观念认为

48
00:02:23.226 --> 00:02:27.223
that everything was safe up to a point, a threshold.
任何事情在一种程度上都是安全的,像一个门槛

49
00:02:27.223 --> 00:02:29.550
It flew in the face of conventional wisdom,
这对于这一观念是很大的冲击

50
00:02:29.550 --> 00:02:33.008
which was huge enthusiasm for the cool new technology
尤其是对于当时新科技,X光机器

51
00:02:33.008 --> 00:02:36.654
of that age, which was the X-ray machine.
的巨大热情

52
00:02:36.654 --> 00:02:40.878
And it flew in the face of doctors' idea of themselves,
而且对于医生对自己的看法也是巨大的冲击

53
00:02:40.878 --> 00:02:44.686
which was as people who helped patients,
因为他们都是帮助病人的

54
00:02:44.686 --> 00:02:47.382
they didn't harm them.
而不是害他们的

55
00:02:47.382 --> 00:02:51.070
Nevertheless, Alice Stewart rushed to publish
不过呢,Alice Stewart还是很快的将她

56
00:02:51.070 --> 00:02:54.654
her preliminary findings in The Lancet in 1956.
最初的发现在1956年的The Lancet杂志中发表了

57
00:02:54.654 --> 00:02:58.662
People got very excited, there was talk of the Nobel Prize,
人们都很兴奋,有人还提到诺贝尔奖的可能

58
00:02:58.662 --> 00:03:00.782
and Alice really was in a big hurry
Alice也很着急

59
00:03:00.782 --> 00:03:04.573
to try to study all the cases of childhood cancer she could find
她想去学习她能找到所有的儿童癌症的资料

60
00:03:04.573 --> 00:03:06.726
before they disappeared.
在他们消失之前

61
00:03:06.726 --> 00:03:11.070
In fact, she need not have hurried.
事实上,她并不需要那么急

62
00:03:11.070 --> 00:03:15.261
It was fully 25 years before the British and medical --
过了25年之后,英国的医学建树--

63
00:03:15.261 --> 00:03:18.133
British and American medical establishments
英国和美国医学建树

64
00:03:18.133 --> 00:03:24.237
abandoned the practice of X-raying pregnant women.
也禁止了给怀孕女人的X光测验

65
00:03:24.237 --> 00:03:29.718
The data was out there, it was open, it was freely available,
数据都是开放的,很容易获得

66
00:03:29.718 --> 00:03:33.942
but nobody wanted to know.
但是没人想知道这一点

67
00:03:33.942 --> 00:03:36.626
A child a week was dying,
每周都有一个小孩在垂死挣扎

68
00:03:36.626 --> 00:03:39.359
but nothing changed.
但就跟啥都没发生一样

69
00:03:39.359 --> 00:03:45.614
Openness alone can't drive change.
开放性无法带来改变

70
00:03:45.614 --> 00:03:51.231
So for 25 years Alice Stewart had a very big fight on her hands.
25年来Alice Stewart在做很大的斗争

71
00:03:51.231 --> 00:03:54.478
So, how did she know that she was right?
所以说,她怎么知道她当时是对的?

72
00:03:54.478 --> 00:03:58.141
Well, she had a fantastic model for thinking.
她有一个极佳的思考模型

73
00:03:58.141 --> 00:04:00.386
She worked with a statistician named George Kneale,
她当时与一位名叫George Kneale的统计学家合作

74
00:04:00.386 --> 00:04:02.770
and George was pretty much everything that Alice wasn't.
而George刚好与Alice正互补

75
00:04:02.770 --> 00:04:05.839
So, Alice was very outgoing and sociable,
Alice非常外向和社交化

76
00:04:05.839 --> 00:04:08.297
and George was a recluse.
而George是个隐居者

77
00:04:08.297 --> 00:04:12.311
Alice was very warm, very empathetic with her patients.
Alice很热情,与她的病人有很多互动

78
00:04:12.311 --> 00:04:16.350
George frankly preferred numbers to people.
而George相比之下更喜欢数字,而不是人们

79
00:04:16.350 --> 00:04:20.328
But he said this fantastic thing about their working relationship.
不过他提到过他们工作关系的极大好处

80
00:04:20.328 --> 00:04:26.664
He said, "My job is to prove Dr. Stewart wrong."
他说:"我的工作就是证明Stewart博士是错的."

81
00:04:26.664 --> 00:04:30.221
He actively sought disconfirmation.
他积极地寻找错误的证明

82
00:04:30.221 --> 00:04:32.558
Different ways of looking at her models,
以不同方式研究她的模型

83
00:04:32.558 --> 00:04:35.815
at her statistics, different ways of crunching the data
她的数据,以及不同方式去利用数据

84
00:04:35.815 --> 00:04:38.878
in order to disprove her.
来证明她是错的

85
00:04:38.878 --> 00:04:44.502
He saw his job as creating conflict around her theories.
他把他自己的工作当作为Alice的理论创造矛盾

86
00:04:44.502 --> 00:04:47.598
Because it was only by not being able to prove
因为只有他无法证明Alice是错的

87
00:04:47.598 --> 00:04:49.966
that she was wrong,
时候,

88
00:04:49.966 --> 00:04:53.087
that George could give Alice the confidence she needed
George就可以带来Alice所需要的自信

89
00:04:53.087 --> 00:04:56.069
to know that she was right.
让她相信她是正确的

90
00:04:56.069 --> 00:05:00.744
It's a fantastic model of collaboration --
这是完美的合作的模型

91
00:05:00.744 --> 00:05:05.751
thinking partners who aren't echo chambers.
由伙伴之前相互补充

92
00:05:05.751 --> 00:05:08.103
I wonder how many of us have,
我想知道有多少人

93
00:05:08.103 --> 00:05:15.022
or dare to have, such collaborators.
有过,或者敢有过这样的合作者

94
00:05:15.022 --> 00:05:18.799
Alice and George were very good at conflict.
Alice和George对于矛盾很擅长

95
00:05:18.799 --> 00:05:21.935
They saw it as thinking.
他们认为这就是思考

96
00:05:21.935 --> 00:05:26.208
So what does that kind of constructive conflict require?
那么这种建设性的矛盾要求什么呢?

97
00:05:26.208 --> 00:05:29.583
Well, first of all, it requires that we find people
首先呢,它需要我们去找到

98
00:05:29.583 --> 00:05:32.231
who are very different from ourselves.
十分不同的人们

99
00:05:32.231 --> 00:05:36.567
That means we have to resist the neurobiological drive,
这意味着我们必须抗拒精神上的推动

100
00:05:36.567 --> 00:05:41.071
which means that we really prefer people mostly like ourselves,
那就是我们更喜欢像我们的人们

101
00:05:41.071 --> 00:05:43.295
and it means we have to seek out people
这意味着我们必须寻找有不同背景,

102
00:05:43.295 --> 00:05:45.767
with different backgrounds, different disciplines,
不同训练,不同方法去思考以及不同经验

103
00:05:45.767 --> 00:05:49.918
different ways of thinking and different experience,
的人们,

104
00:05:49.918 --> 00:05:53.783
and find ways to engage with them.
而且还要去想办法与他们交流

105
00:05:53.783 --> 00:05:58.427
That requires a lot of patience and a lot of energy.
这需要很多热情和能量

106
00:05:58.427 --> 00:06:00.238
And the more I've thought about this,
我想这一点想的越多,

107
00:06:00.238 --> 00:06:05.399
the more I think, really, that that's a kind of love.
真的,我觉得这是一种爱

108
00:06:05.399 --> 00:06:08.468
Because you simply won't commit that kind of energy
因为如果你不在乎的话,

109
00:06:08.468 --> 00:06:13.159
and time if you don't really care.
你不可能付出那么多能量的

110
00:06:13.159 --> 00:06:17.619
And it also means that we have to be prepared to change our minds.
这还意味着我们必须准备好去改变我们的想法

111
00:06:17.619 --> 00:06:19.983
Alice's daughter told me
Alice的女儿告诉我

112
00:06:19.983 --> 00:06:23.095
that every time Alice went head-to-head with a fellow scientist,
每次Alice去和一个同事科学家会面,

113
00:06:23.095 --> 00:06:27.279
they made her think and think and think again.
他们都让她一遍一遍的思考.

114
00:06:27.279 --> 00:06:31.297
"My mother," she said, "My mother didn't enjoy a fight,
"我的母亲",她说,"我的母亲不喜欢争吵,

115
00:06:31.297 --> 00:06:36.439
but she was really good at them."
但是她却很擅长."

116
00:06:36.439 --> 00:06:40.609
So it's one thing to do that in a one-to-one relationship.
因此这在一对一的关系中是一个方面

117
00:06:40.609 --> 00:06:43.896
But it strikes me that the biggest problems we face,
但这使我想到那些我们面对过的最大难题

118
00:06:43.896 --> 00:06:46.770
many of the biggest disasters that we've experienced,
经历过的最严重的灾难,

119
00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:48.721
mostly haven't come from individuals,
大多都不是由个人引起的

120
00:06:48.721 --> 00:06:50.609
they've come from organizations,
而是从组织而来的

121
00:06:50.609 --> 00:06:52.617
some of them bigger than countries,
有些比国家还大

122
00:06:52.617 --> 00:06:54.877
many of them capable of affecting hundreds,
大多数都有影响上百人的能力

123
00:06:54.877 --> 00:06:58.880
thousands, even millions of lives.
甚至上千人,上百万人

124
00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:03.318
So how do organizations think?
那么这些组织是怎么想的呢?

125
00:07:03.318 --> 00:07:07.344
Well, for the most part, they don't.
其实大多数情况下,他们是不思考的

126
00:07:07.344 --> 00:07:10.337
And that isn't because they don't want to,
这不是因为他们不想

127
00:07:10.337 --> 00:07:12.742
it's really because they can't.
而是因为他们无法

128
00:07:12.742 --> 00:07:16.089
And they can't because the people inside of them
因为在组织里面的人

129
00:07:16.089 --> 00:07:20.297
are too afraid of conflict.
对于矛盾有一种恐惧心理

130
00:07:20.297 --> 00:07:23.161
In surveys of European and American executives,
在对欧洲和美国行政人员的调查中，

131
00:07:23.161 --> 00:07:26.131
fully 85 percent of them acknowledged
有百分之85都承认

132
00:07:26.131 --> 00:07:29.648
that they had issues or concerns at work
他们有一些他们自己不敢说出

133
00:07:29.648 --> 00:07:33.281
that they were afraid to raise.
的话题和意见

134
00:07:33.281 --> 00:07:36.440
Afraid of the conflict that that would provoke,
对可能产生的矛盾有恐惧心理

135
00:07:36.440 --> 00:07:38.808
afraid to get embroiled in arguments
不想被缠绕在他们不知道怎么

136
00:07:38.808 --> 00:07:40.839
that they did not know how to manage,
处理的争论中

137
00:07:40.839 --> 00:07:45.416
and felt that they were bound to lose.
而且感到他们肯定会输

138
00:07:45.416 --> 00:07:51.593
Eighty-five percent is a really big number.
百分之85可是很大的数字

139
00:07:51.593 --> 00:07:54.408
It means that organizations mostly can't do
这意味着大多数组织没法做

140
00:07:54.408 --> 00:07:56.736
what George and Alice so triumphantly did.
George和Alice成功做到的事情

141
00:07:56.736 --> 00:08:01.135
They can't think together.
他们不能心往一处想

142
00:08:01.135 --> 00:08:03.376
And it means that people like many of us,
而这意味着跟我们一样的许多

143
00:08:03.376 --> 00:08:05.560
who have run organizations,
带领组织的人

144
00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:09.127
and gone out of our way to try to find the very best people we can,
都在尽可能找到他们能找到最好的人

145
00:08:09.127 --> 00:08:15.400
mostly fail to get the best out of them.
不过大多数都失败了

146
00:08:15.400 --> 00:08:18.736
So how do we develop the skills that we need?
那么我们怎样培养我们需要的技巧呢?

147
00:08:18.736 --> 00:08:22.819
Because it does take skill and practice, too.
因为这的确需要一些技巧和练习

148
00:08:22.819 --> 00:08:26.233
If we aren't going to be afraid of conflict,
如果我们不惧怕矛盾的话,

149
00:08:26.233 --> 00:08:28.392
we have to see it as thinking,
我们必须把它当作思考

150
00:08:28.392 --> 00:08:32.728
and then we have to get really good at it.
然后我们必须变得很擅长

151
00:08:32.728 --> 00:08:36.992
So, recently, I worked with an executive named Joe,
因此,最近,我在和一个叫Joe的行政人员工作,

152
00:08:36.992 --> 00:08:40.464
and Joe worked for a medical device company.
Jow为一家医疗设备公司工作

153
00:08:40.464 --> 00:08:43.439
And Joe was very worried about the device that he was working on.
他很担心他正在工作的这台医疗设备

154
00:08:43.439 --> 00:08:46.464
He thought that it was too complicated
实在太复杂了

155
00:08:46.464 --> 00:08:48.328
and he thought that its complexity
以至于这台机器可能

156
00:08:48.328 --> 00:08:52.595
created margins of error that could really hurt people.
会产生一些错误去伤害人们

157
00:08:52.595 --> 00:08:56.735
He was afraid of doing damage to the patients he was trying to help.
他很害怕去伤害那些他想帮助的人们

158
00:08:56.735 --> 00:08:59.040
But when he looked around his organization,
不过他看了看周围的人,

159
00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:03.501
nobody else seemed to be at all worried.
没人似乎有这种担心

160
00:09:03.501 --> 00:09:06.056
So, he didn't really want to say anything.
因此,他不想把自己的想法说出来

161
00:09:06.056 --> 00:09:08.240
After all, maybe they knew something he didn't.
毕竟,其他人可能知道他有不知道的东西,

162
00:09:08.240 --> 00:09:10.824
Maybe he'd look stupid.
这样他会看起来很愚蠢

163
00:09:10.824 --> 00:09:13.030
But he kept worrying about it,
但是他始终非常担心,

164
00:09:13.030 --> 00:09:16.076
and he worried about it so much that he got to the point
以至于他到达一种程度

165
00:09:16.076 --> 00:09:18.235
where he thought the only thing he could do
他觉得唯一可以做的事情

166
00:09:18.235 --> 00:09:22.365
was leave a job he loved.
就是辞掉他热爱的工作

167
00:09:22.365 --> 00:09:26.365
In the end, Joe and I found a way
最后,Joe和我找到一个

168
00:09:26.365 --> 00:09:28.220
for him to raise his concerns.
提升他担心关注度的方法

169
00:09:28.220 --> 00:09:31.091
And what happened then is what almost always
结果呢,总是发生的事情

170
00:09:31.091 --> 00:09:32.685
happens in this situation.
果然再一次发生了.

171
00:09:32.685 --> 00:09:35.906
It turned out everybody had exactly the same
所有人其实都有着

172
00:09:35.906 --> 00:09:37.652
questions and doubts.
同样的问题和怀疑

173
00:09:37.652 --> 00:09:41.684
So now Joe had allies. They could think together.
所以现在Joe和他的伙伴.他们可以往一处去思考

174
00:09:41.684 --> 00:09:44.948
And yes, there was a lot of conflict and debate
当然,这其中有很多的矛盾和辩论

175
00:09:44.948 --> 00:09:49.252
and argument, but that allowed everyone around the table
不过这使得所有人都变得

176
00:09:49.252 --> 00:09:53.332
to be creative, to solve the problem,
有创造力,都能去解决问题

177
00:09:53.332 --> 00:09:57.660
and to change the device.
去改变这台设备

178
00:09:57.660 --> 00:10:01.036
Joe was what a lot of people might think of
Joe有点像是大多数认为的

179
00:10:01.036 --> 00:10:03.308
as a whistle-blower,
揭发者

180
00:10:03.308 --> 00:10:06.023
except that like almost all whistle-blowers,
只不过像所有揭发者一样,

181
00:10:06.023 --> 00:10:08.396
he wasn't a crank at all,
他不是在异想天开

182
00:10:08.396 --> 00:10:11.844
he was passionately devoted to the organization
他有激情地为组织付出

183
00:10:11.844 --> 00:10:15.292
and the higher purposes that that organization served.
以及为组织的目标所努力

184
00:10:15.292 --> 00:10:19.108
But he had been so afraid of conflict,
不过他对于矛盾太过于惧怕

185
00:10:19.108 --> 00:10:24.188
until finally he became more afraid of the silence.
直到最后沉默对他来说更为可怕

186
00:10:24.188 --> 00:10:26.047
And when he dared to speak,
而当他敢于说出口的时候,

187
00:10:26.047 --> 00:10:29.445
he discovered much more inside himself
他发现了更多的自己

188
00:10:29.445 --> 00:10:34.687
and much more give in the system than he had ever imagined.
以及他从未想象过的对于系统的贡献

189
00:10:34.687 --> 00:10:38.018
And his colleagues don't think of him as a crank.
而且他的同事没觉得他的想法是天方夜谭

190
00:10:38.018 --> 00:10:43.146
They think of him as a leader.
他们认为他是个领导者

191
00:10:43.146 --> 00:10:47.514
So, how do we have these conversations more easily
所以说,我们怎么样才能更简单

192
00:10:47.514 --> 00:10:49.427
and more often?
更经常地来发起这些对话呢?

193
00:10:49.427 --> 00:10:51.413
Well, the University of Delft
嗯, Delft 大学要求

194
00:10:51.413 --> 00:10:53.810
requires that its PhD students
它所有的博士学生

195
00:10:53.810 --> 00:10:57.723
have to submit five statements that they're prepared to defend.
必须提交他们已经准备好可以进行辩护的5个陈述

196
00:10:57.723 --> 00:11:01.107
It doesn't really matter what the statements are about,
这些陈述是什么都无所谓

197
00:11:01.107 --> 00:11:04.899
what matters is that the candidates are willing and able
重要的是这些选手们愿意而且有能力

198
00:11:04.899 --> 00:11:07.502
to stand up to authority.
对权威提出挑战

199
00:11:07.502 --> 00:11:09.866
I think it's a fantastic system,
我认为这是一个极棒的系统

200
00:11:09.866 --> 00:11:12.379
but I think leaving it to PhD candidates
不过我觉得把这些留给博士生

201
00:11:12.379 --> 00:11:16.684
is far too few people, and way too late in life.
太少了,而且太晚了

202
00:11:16.684 --> 00:11:19.850
I think we need to be teaching these skills
我认为我们应该向所以小孩和大人

203
00:11:19.850 --> 00:11:23.930
to kids and adults at every stage of their development,
都来教授这些技巧

204
00:11:23.930 --> 00:11:26.379
if we want to have thinking organizations
如果我们想要能够思考的组织

205
00:11:26.379 --> 00:11:30.026
and a thinking society.
和社会

206
00:11:30.026 --> 00:11:35.644
The fact is that most of the biggest catastrophes that we've witnessed
事实上,那些我们曾经见证过的最大的灾难,

207
00:11:35.644 --> 00:11:42.035
rarely come from information that is secret or hidden.
很少是由于一些隐藏的或者秘密的信息而产生

208
00:11:42.035 --> 00:11:46.339
It comes from information that is freely available and out there,
都是由那些公开的信息而造成的

209
00:11:46.339 --> 00:11:48.723
but that we are willfully blind to,
不过我们只不是完全忽略了而已

210
00:11:48.723 --> 00:11:51.851
because we can't handle, don't want to handle,
因为我们不想去处理引起

211
00:11:51.851 --> 00:11:56.258
the conflict that it provokes.
的各种麻烦和矛盾

212
00:11:56.258 --> 00:11:59.187
But when we dare to break that silence,
但是当我们愿意去打破这种沉默

213
00:11:59.187 --> 00:12:01.844
or when we dare to see,
或者我们敢于看到

214
00:12:01.844 --> 00:12:04.099
and we create conflict,
并且制造矛盾

215
00:12:04.099 --> 00:12:06.724
we enable ourselves and the people around us
我们使得我们以及周围的人

216
00:12:06.724 --> 00:12:10.970
to do our very best thinking.
进行最有效的思考

217
00:12:10.970 --> 00:12:14.346
Open information is fantastic,
公开信息是很棒的

218
00:12:14.346 --> 00:12:17.530
open networks are essential.
公开的网络很关键

219
00:12:17.530 --> 00:12:19.507
But the truth won't set us free
但是事实不会让我们自由

220
00:12:19.507 --> 00:12:23.271
until we develop the skills and the habit and the talent
除非我们拥有技能,习惯,天赋,

221
00:12:23.271 --> 00:12:27.408
and the moral courage to use it.
以及道德上的勇气去利用它

222
00:12:27.408 --> 00:12:31.168
Openness isn't the end.
公开并不是一个结束

223
00:12:31.168 --> 00:12:33.810
It's the beginning.
它只是一个开始

224
00:12:33.810 --> 00:12:45.289
(Applause)
(鼓掌)